         <abstract>
            <p>For a polynomial, P, of degree 2n - 2, there exists a relation between the values of P and the values of its first derivative, P', at the n abscissa points x&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;,⋯, x&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;, ∑&lt;sub&gt;i=1&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt; [ a&lt;sub&gt;iP&lt;/sub&gt;(x&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt;) + b&lt;sub&gt;iP&lt;/sub&gt;'(x&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt;) ] = 0. Replacing P by a differentiable function y yields ∑&lt;sub&gt;i=1&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt; [ a&lt;sub&gt;iy&lt;/sub&gt;(x&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt;) + b&lt;sub&gt;iy&lt;/sub&gt;'(x&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt;) ] = E(y, x). These relations are obtained and the error function E(y, x) is given explicitly.</p>
          </abstract>
